1.What is the difference between Named Export, Default export and * as export?
 A:- Name export :
        Export thing by their names.
        Example : // math.js
                export const add = (a, b) => a + b;
                export const subtract = (a, b) => a - b;
        Import:
        import { add, subtract } from "./math";
        ->Rules:
            1.Must use same names
            2.Must use {}
        ->When to use
            1.When you have multiple exports
            2.Utilities, helpers, constants

    Default Export :
        Export one main thing from a file.
        Example://Header.js
                const Header = () => {
                return <h1>Header</h1>;
                };
                export default Header;
        Import:
        import Header from "./Header";
        ->Rules:
            1.No {} needed
            2.You can rename it anything
        ->when to use
            1.When file has one main component
            2.React components mostly use this

    * as Export(Namespace Import) : 
        Import everything and store inside an object (math)
        Example :// math.js
            export const add = (a, b) => a + b;
            export const subtract = (a, b) => a - b;

            import * as math from "./math";
            So internally:
            const math = {
                        add,
                        subtract
                        };

            math.add(2, 3);
            math.subtract(5, 2);
        ->When to use
            1.When file has many exports
            2.When you want clean grouping

